post_caption: Exploring Tanjong Pagar last weekend. I used to work in this district few years back and i love how it is located in the CBD district yet you can find neighbourhood vibe just along duxton road. More than just cafes and bbq restaurants, you can even find wet market and pasar there. Favourite lunch time meal is roast meat at realty centre.

Did you know that there are a whopping 90 skyscrapers in our little red dot?⠀
⠀
Interestingly though, in Singapore, it is forbidden to build buildings higher than 280 meters. ⠀
⠀
The tallest skyscraper though stands at 290m, like a proud rebel, flouting this rule (ok..ok..they sought a special permission from the Urban Redevelopment Authority)⠀
⠀
The latest addition to this already-impressive skyline chooses to wow us with it’s shape rather than it’s height. A shiny rounded glass dome that floats on the Singapore river. They say it’s design was inspired by the Pantheon in Rome. A Roman temple inspiring the new-age temple of the Gen Z ,aka, the Apple Showroom. Rather apt.⠀
⠀
There she stands, sun-bathing, acting as a mirror for the skyline..⠀
⠀
You wonder, “Is this what they mean by reflected glory?” :P⠀
.
.⠀
D&I spent an entire morning shooting with this beautiful backdrop! It was our first photoshoot in almost 6 months and we had an absolute ball. Are you guys having fun exploring your home cities as well?

Rediscover Singapore ‘in Saris’...

There is an upside to going nowhere during this pandemic.
While borders stay shut and leisure travel remains a forlorn hope, we at DD have decided to explore and checkout our own backyards..
While maintaining social distance in a maximum group of 5, we have set out to enjoy the beauty of our garden city, via all the NParks around the little red dot! 

Follow Rachel as she flags off this journey for the DemureDrapes Singapore! 
Here she travels to 
Sunplaza park in Tampines, 
Bedok Reservoir park in Bedok, 
the Tampines eco green Diversity and Forest trails, 
Pasir Ris mangroves,
Changi Board Walk,
East Coast Park,
Henderson Waves, 
Telok Blangah park,
Mount Faber..

To start the walk tours for  rediscovering Singapore, as team DD explores different parks, we will share details.

Let’s together rediscover the Jewel we live in..

The clip below is a small trailer to Rachel’s journey. Click the YouTube link below to watch the full video.

Always have a nostalgic feeling everytime i visit library..⁣
I was a bookworm back then when i was in High School, spent a lot of my time at the school library.. ⁣
My personal favourite is reading about anatomy, biology and history.. and i love reading novels too, i could finish reading a novel overnight 🙈⁣
⁣
What is your favourite reading? ⁣
⁣
This photo taken at Library @ Orchard. ⁣
Located on the third and fourth floors of Orchardgateway, the library splits into The Studio and The Loft which features a vast array of titles, as well as programme zones. ⁣
⁣
Can you spot me btw? 😂 I was wearing stripes dress, kinda blend with the books.. ⁣

It has been the longest time since I picked up an actual camera. Well, probably been 4 years since! The last time, I was shooting on a Canon dslr (had it since 2008) so it was a little bulky, heavy and a little difficult to travel with. Recently, I bought myself a new mirrorless camera, and I’ve been really happy with it. It is small, light and compact.
-
I’m usually really shy to take my camera out and practice any “street photography”. So I am really chuffed how this one came out.

It was not easy at first to do it regularly.But with consistency you will get through it. 

I started with brisk walk. Finding trails,parks and other places that I can explore in Singapore. (Kan #rediscoversingapore) slowly I regain back my stamina and since then, I enjoy doing it. Oh and the lovely morning sun! 

Once you start, do not give up! No matter how hard it is. Because health is wealth and your mental health matters too.❤️

【必去新加坡的小土耳其｜著街區太迷人了】

19世紀法國軍事家拿破侖曾說：「如果世界是一個國家，它的首都一定會是伊斯坦堡。」 19世紀的法國詩人拉馬丁則在遊歷過伊斯坦堡後說：「如果只能看這個世界一眼，那就看伊斯坦堡吧！」
	
橫跨兩大洲與博斯普魯斯海峽的伊斯坦堡，舊名為「君士坦丁堡」，曾是羅馬帝國、拜佔庭帝國與鄂圖曼帝國的首都，如今更是土耳其共和國的第一大城。
	
如此迷人的地方究竟是怎樣的？雖然今年前去土耳其🇹🇷旅遊的計劃泡湯了，我在新加坡甘榜格南(Kampong Glam 穆斯林的聚居區）的Bussorah street 巴梭拉街貌似找到了答案～這條街如同是個濃縮迷你版的土耳其🥰
	
💁‍♀️在Bussorah street（通常也有人會籠統地稱這裡為Arab street）除了可以打卡新加坡著名的回教堂Sultan Mosque，還可以近距離感受到帶著古拜佔庭與鄂圖曼元素的土耳其風情。61Bussorah street是間迷你版的grand bazaar 大巴扎，擺滿了繽紛多彩的鄂圖曼風格的馬薩克玻璃燈，也能看到用伊茲尼克磁磚做的的鍋碗瓢盆～都很喜歡！
💁‍♀️有美美的工藝品當然也少不了各種地中海風味和土耳其的美食。我第一次吃到有著舉世聞名土耳其「pizza」之稱的pide，烤肉拼盤和蘋果茶就在著兒🥰
💁‍♀️bussorah street是我很喜歡這個地方，無限回返！各種民族風的東西和美食都可以在這裡找到～之前寫的halal北歐烘培坊也在著哦～也有Arabica% 咖啡館。祝大家天天開心～下集我再多寫寫這裡的土耳其甜點和咖啡，和逛中東地攤之旅！

A simple step out of your comfort zone can make you realise that nothing is impossible, as long as you allow your heart to embrace whatever comes.

Being someone with height phobia and having occasions of rolling out of my own bed, sleeping on the upper bunk of a double decker bed is considered as a simple step out of comfort zone.

👩🏻 Want to go duck tour?
👨🏻 Expensive not? How much?
👩🏻 Now got 25% off. When tourists come back, no more discount le.
👨🏻 Ok lah.

🤣🤣🤣

Anyway we had lots of fun! That moment the boat swishing into the water was the highlight i think 😂Though it was raining quite heavily and the sky was gloomy, still i felt Singapore’s landscape is so pretty 😍

Amidst the high rise buildings and popular tourist attractions, we also saw foreign workers queuing up in an orderly manner at the Float for Covid swaps.

While we enjoyed the beautiful scenery, clean and safe environment, we were reminded of the #unsungheroes who make all these possible. Indeed a special time to take the duck tour. 😊
.

The rich and colourful world of Chinese Orchestral music is so all-encompassing that even animals are regularly being featured. 
Under the baton of SCO’s Assistant Conductor Moses Gay, veteran musicians team up with their younger colleagues to bring you in for a Chinese Orchestra style wild ride through the animal kingdom. Feel the power of nature and join us in a rhapsodic evening of Untamed Melodies! Get your e-tickets now, link in bio!
.
.
华乐世界千变万化，就连动物也从不缺席。
.
.
奔驰的骏马，威武的老虎，亮丽的孔雀，可爱的熊猫……几十年来，多少华乐大师以这群人类的好朋友为题谱曲。牠们的一举一动，被幻化成跳跃的音符，“声”机处处！
让我们在新加坡华乐团助理指挥倪恩辉的带领下，与乐团多位资深与青年乐手组成的最佳拍挡，一起走进华乐的动物世界，感受大自然的力量，一起狂欢吧！点击bio链接购票!
.
.

Ideas include trying out a 15 minute homemade kaya recipe from @cedelesingapore, participating in the HDB Cool Ideas Hack 2020 or a Mooncake Baking Competition, go on a virtual exploration in Singapore to hike the old Jurong Line, visiting art exhibitions or attending flea markets.

You can also check out virtual events such as the TLC Children's festival, participate in the @samaritansofsingapore  #HOWRU Virtual Walkathon and/or @theescapeartistsg's FREE mobile game (iLiad: Legend's Call) to claim a FREE $5 Grab (first 800 players!) voucher when you register and complete the game!

There are weekends i feel like doing nothing just cuddling at home with LO @dearbbkai but somehow i feel so guilty that i also need to be productive over the weekends.. ⁣
⁣
Mind and body are exhausted but i just need to capture moments as much as possible, creating contents.. ⁣
Decided to stay at home over this weekend as i need to rest.. ⁣
I was having restless night and worrying, as @dearbbkai now actively roll over here and there and sometimes i found him sleep on his tummy.. I keep on adjusting his position to face up but he ended up sleep at the side.. ⁣

Rediscover Singapore ‘in Saris’...

There is an upside to going nowhere during this pandemic.
While borders stay shut and leisure travel remains a forlorn hope, we at DD have decided to explore and checkout our own backyards..
While maintaining social distance in a maximum group of 5, we have set out to enjoy the beauty of our garden city, via all the NParks around the little red dot! 

Follow Rachel as she flags off this journey for the DemureDrapes Singapore! 
Here she travels to 
Sunplaza park in Tampines, 
Bedok Reservoir park in Bedok, 
the Tampines eco green Diversity and Forest trails, 
Pasir Ris mangroves,
Changi Board Walk,
East Coast Park,
Henderson Waves, 
Telok Blangah park,
Mount Faber..

To start the walk tours for  rediscovering Singapore, as team DD explores different parks, we will share details.

Let’s together rediscover the Jewel we live in..

Behind the Scenes: Forgotten
|
How long will our appreciation for essential workers last? Will we continue thanking the aunties and uncles who work hard behind the scenes so that we can pose infront of picturesque backgrounds for our instagram feed? Our gratitute towards essential workers should not be momentary. Instead the habit of saying "Thank you for your hardwork today" - should be a habit cultivated and ingrained in us. 
|
I am grateful to have captured one of the most meaningful and significant moment during my trip to Gardens by the Bay.

Pasir Ris mangroves is small, but has a lovely boardwalk running through it. It allows a close up look at the fascinating mangroves! Such as the mud lobster mounds which are rarely seen nowadays. The boardwalk meanders among tall mangrove trees. Allowing us a closer look at the plants as well as the animals living in the mud and pools and streams. The boardwalk leads to a lovely little shelter on Sungei Tampines. It's a great spot to look at birds and fishes and snakes! Pasir Ris is the only place on the mainland where we can easily view rare mangrove trees.

【新加坡海底世界｜海之味夢幻美味晚餐】

不知你是不是也會覺得海洋包羅萬象但又深不可測，令人眷戀～在宇宙前我們就像大生命之一滴，卑微、渺小的，而一滴一滴的活動生長合成了整個宇宙的進化。對我來說，望著浩瀚無垠的海底世界很療癒～從而心寬了，人樂觀開朗了。你有同感嗎？😉
	
每次生日能與身邊的人一起度過美好時光，都感到額外的感恩🥰今年生日剛好遇上了#海之味 在 8月28日- 10月31日期間，推出儀式感爆棚的晚餐活動 #aquagastronomy ，特別喜歡。活動期間，餐廳特別搭建了有如繁星閃爍的泡泡屋，主菜還有個發光的驚喜，我就不多寫了不然你去的時候就沒有驚喜了哈哈～

💁‍♀️晚餐主打海洋為主題的4道菜餚，$98++ 一位 （rws會員價）/ $118++ （非會員價）。1萬4千種的海洋生物尤其是巨大的#mantaray #蝠鱝 盡收眼底，加上海鮮美味佳餚，我覺得在新加坡真的好物超所值哈哈！非常適合慶祝開心日子的氣派餐廳。 大人小孩都會喜歡的餐廳～菜單是定好的（圖5），如果有忌口的話也可以通知餐廳哦～

💁‍♀️還有送小禮物，太暖心了！送的是餐廳自家調配的海帶鹽，我好喜歡！還沒試味道，但馬上聯想到le beurre bordier著名的海帶牛油，所以也想拿來試試搭配牛油哈哈！主廚建議可以加在pasta里～還送了一張#WuYanrong 畫的Giant Pacific #octopus 的明信片，贊哦👍

💁‍♀️需要預先定位哦～可以上新加坡淘沙名勝世界 @rwsentosa 官網或打電話定位，詳情 （圖9）～祝大家天天好心情，我們下集去「非洲「🥰

Here are 5.5 reasons why I’m hoping to score the Sony ZV-1 camera 🙏🏼:
1. One-push bokeh switch (and soft skin enhancement) makes it easy to take professional looking portraits.
2. Advanced image stabilization means steady shots to show movement - I might even be able to take footage of the city skyline while running along this route!
3. Lightweight body makes the Sony ZV-1 convenient to carry around while traveling (or rather while embarking on my #RediscoverSingapore adventures for now).
4. One push product showcase setting would make it easy to shoot close-up shots of beautifully plated food and drinks while cafe hopping.
5. Clear audio recording functionality that blocks out wind and background noise means that I won’t need to do a separate voiceover narration like in this video for future vlogs!
5.5 Ergonomic grip means that I won’t get a hand cramp from awkwardly gripping a large camera for a long time!

I can’t believe it’s been 10 years of Fremantle Seafood Market. I remember coming down to the opening when I was still in University. Since then, we’ve changed and rebranded ourselves. First when Clarke Quay’s main dining demographic was tourist, we added Singaporean styled seafood to our menu to give our guests a flavour of Singapore next to the scenic views of the Singapore River. Today, with no tourist, we’ve assessed our menu to include a wide range of live seafood, partnered with local seafood farmers like Ah Hua Kelong, Australian Breweries and Vineyards to give our guests a classic Australian “Freo” experience. I hope this takes you on the trip we’re all so missing! #rediscoversingapore #creativeeateries 📷@brandcellar

The word Bharata is a mnemonic, consisting of "bha"–"ra"–"ta". According to a belief, bha stands for bhava (feelings, emotions), ra stands for raga (melody, framework for musical notes), and ta stands for tala (rhythm). The term Natya is a Sanskrit word for "dance".

It was 1930 when the world’s first tropical dairy farm was established at the base of Bukit Timah Hill. Originally, the area was earmarked for pig farming but after an outbreak of swine fever, Fred Heron, Managing Director of Cold Storage, decided that there was a need for high quality, fresh milk in Singapore and converted the area to a milk farm instead.

He brought in 24 Friesian cows to Singapore from Holland and Australia and started a dairy farm in the area. Hence, setting down the basis for Dairy Farm Nature Park’s name.

Friesian cattle are a breed known for their dairy production. They are completely alien to the tropics and the Singapore dairy farm was an oddity that attracted a fair amount of worldwide attention.

Today, the cows are gone. Nonetheless, they still resound with the name Dairy Farm Nature Park.

Formerly known as Lorong East Coast Road in 1934, this road was renamed after Cheong Koon Seng, an auctioneer & real estate agent. ⁠
⁠
These  archetypal pre-war shophouses along 𝐊𝐨𝐨𝐧 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐠 𝐑𝐨𝐚𝐝 is a display some of the finest examples of #Peranakan architecture in #Singapore ⁠🇸🇬⁠
The most notable feature is the narrow, yet eclectic embellished front facade. ⁠

The #Best #calamari in #singapore , and a really nice #club with #great #service . We were here just before #cb #circuitbreaker in April, and 5.5mths later, we are back. I had many calamari before, but this is the only one I couldn't forget and I just want more of it. My friend and I are such fans we decided to get our own plate each next time. Not only was the batter really crispy and #delicious , but the spicy #mayo too. 

Plus,  the club has its own pool for that #instagram moment,  not so much for swim as now, it's limited to 20mins only. A bird drank my coconut whilst we were in the pool, and an attentive staff told us on our return that he had cleared the coconut and offered me a new one. Super great and responsible service eh? 

We were here 2x and we still love the food and #vibe here.  Hope to be back again, and with no crowds (surprisingly being a weekday, it was rather full!).

Weather was perfect,  wasn't hot, wasn't rainy. I was really happy, thanks to my friend's indulgence to also have a dip in the pool with me (she wasn't quite feeling the mood for the pool).

Archaeological excavations of artefacts such as Chinese coins or ceramics in Singapore, which dated back to the period of the reign of Emperor Zhenzong of Song (998–1022) and Emperor Renzong of Song (1023–1063), indicated that Chinese merchants or traders had already visited Singapore since Song dynasty. But when Singapore became a Straits Settlement, there were very few Chinese. After Singapore became a British trading post as part of the Straits Settlement, the first batch of Chinese came from Malaysia, predominantly from Malacca and Penan. The Chinese quickly formed the majority of the population in Singapore. After interacting with diverse influences over many years, Chinese culture in Singapore has evolved in a way quite unlike other communities around the world. No matter who you are, there is always room to discover (rediscover ) what it means to be a Chinese Singapo人

post_caption:
Being stuck in a little island ain’t so bad. Let’s  make the best of it to rediscover Singapore 🇸🇬 !
*****
My friends and I took a short 10
mins bum boat ride to Pulau Ubin. We hired a premium mountain bike ($15) and cycled from east to west of the little island. We hiked the tallest hill Bukit Pakau which is only 74m in height but the views were rewarding! The most challenging cycling trail was on our way to Chek Jawa wetlands. You need strong thighs and a good momentum cycling uphill on rocky trails. Otherwise you get off the bike and just walk. We saw hornbills, monkeys, wild boar of all ages and other friendly fellow cyclists. We end our day with a late seafood lunch and a well deserving cold coconut!
*****
Bum boat rides available at Changi Point Ferry Terminal for $4 per pax, one way.
*****

63km lsd done yesterday covering west to east to northeastern Singapore.. Selfie at the Sunset strip along Punggol Reservoir with the dome-shaped trellis (Jewel Bridge) as a background! 😊

Last month, I went out of Singapore's mainland. But no, I didn't travel out of Singapore. Some of my friends and family thought that I can now travel overseas; but sadly, that's not the case. I'm still confined in this tiny red dot.

I miss the feeling of traveling, of leaving my comfort zone and explore new places. For now, the Southern Islands are the farthest places I can travel to, and that's okay. 

Kusu island is one of the many Southern Islands located off the southern coast of Singapore. It is home to a beautiful Chinese temple, a sacred Malay shrine, a cute tortoise shelter and 2 beaches.

I have visited this island twice and it's still one of my favorite islands in Singapore. It is just so beautiful and it doesn't feel like Singapore at all. 

If you are planning to visit Kusu island, please bring your own food and drink because you won't be able to buy any on the island. Before you go, do read my detailed guide for visiting Kusu Island. Link in bio!

During the Second World War, a hill in the park was the site of one of the last and fiercest battles fought by the Malay Regiment against the invading Japanese army, the Battle of Bukit Chandu. 
Kent Ridge Park is part of the Pasir Panjang Historic District, which focuses on World War II battlefield events in western Singapore. 
Near to the top of the ridge, there is a commemorative heritage site marker which shows the area where the Battle of Pasir Panjang of 1942 was fought.

With a strong background of cultural and ethnic diversity, the architecture of Singapore displays a range of influences and styles from different periods and may be divided into the more traditional pre-World War II colonial period, and the largely modern post-war and post-colonial period. And I love it! ❤️ Behind this facade there are layers and layers of memories, each telling a different aspect of the areas history. But the constant remodelling of Singapore has had one positive impact: Contemporary Singapore architecture has a strong focus on sustainability! By encouraging the adoption of innovative architectural design and energy-saving technologies, Singapore has emerged as a model of green building in Asia! The history of Sri Srinivasa Perumal temple dates back to the late 1800s when influential community leaders like Mr Arunachala Pillay, Mr Cootaperumal Pillay, Mr Ramasamy Pillay, Mr Appasamy Pillay, Mr Chockalingam Pillay and Mr Ramasamy Jamidar, all of whom had close working links with the East Indian Company, wanted to build a Hindu temple for Vaishnavite worship.

These men got together and purchased a piece of land measuring 2 acres 2 woods and 24 poles from the East India Company in 1851 for 26 rupees and 8 annas (at that period of time Indian currency was still used in the Settlement of Singapore). The temple they built in 1885 was referred to as the Narasinga Perumal Kovil.

This grew as more devotees donated land to the temple.

The 20-metres-tall impressive Gopuram is a relatively recent addition, built in 1966.

Mama zi used to force feed her by making balls of spinach and rice and also by making her walk around the house and play and then come back to eat the left over spinach. Sometimes this would take up to 2 hours 😂😂😂😂 

Now, at the dining  table and spice zi kitchen our moringa leaves dish is the first to finish. Mama zi's trick of adding dried chili and desicated coconut has transformed this dish and made it a crowd favourite 😊 

Also, as baby  T grows older, bitterness as a taste seems to grow on her 🤭

I guess the more you explore, the more you will find..

🥐🥖☕𝑹𝒆𝒅𝒊𝒔𝒄𝒐𝒗𝒆𝒓𝒊𝒏𝒈 𝑺𝒊𝒏𝒈𝒂𝒑𝒐𝒓𝒆! Spent a lovely morning catching up with the ex schoolmate at this quaint bakery cafe and didn't realise how much the shops have changed since a long time ago when I used to hang out along the stretch during my schooling years.😑

If the bakery selection reminds you of a certain more renowned one😜, I have to say the food is slightly less expensive here but waaaayyy better in quality and taste! I really love the 3 items we selected: 🥓🥧 Bacon Quiche, Chicken and Cheese Bun and Mini Pain au Chocolat. The quiche was super yummy, the bacon and cheese filling went really well with the buttery pie crust. The Chicken and Cheese Bun was also very good, I like how the milk bread was slightly crispy and the filling was the right hint of savoury chicken-pieness though I wish there was a bit more of it. 

The 🥐🍫Pain au Chocolat was light and shatteringly delicious! You know how some chocolate croissants tend to leave a heavy taste on the palate...for me this was almost perfect and the chocolate was not too sweet. It has just the right hints of cocoa and 🧈 butter. I would exercise an entire week just to eat this again soon! 😅 

Post-note: I found out some interesting facts about the ingredients used in their breads from their website and the head chef is a very prolific baker from Japan. I would definitely need to come back soon! 😁
.

【新加坡$1能買到啥？Spotlight布料手工店】

每次到#Plaza Singapura商場，一定會到Spotlight布料手工店看看。我買了一塊布做成一個簡單小小的午餐包～很喜歡哈哈～這裡時不時會有促銷，這次看到兩樣$1的東西（圖一）～

💁‍♀️這裡裁縫材料的價格比鄰里的高一些，像是拉鍊，線🧵的小樣的東西我不會在這裡買～但這裡樣式很多，花樣也多元～也有質感很好的模特兒架 （圖四）

💁‍♀️除了裁縫和編織材料，我也很喜歡這裡美美的家居用品和裝飾好物，風格偏向於澳洲海邊度假風，蠻愜意的。也有些可愛創意的開瓶器（圖六）。大門前面擺了一個輕奢風金色的飲料推車好喜歡 （圖七）！

💁‍♀️這次還看到一個很特別的乳膠枕頭，koo elite copper pillow。有一層像是帶有銅材質的表層。我按了按，是我喜歡的那種乳膠的彈性！但那個copper表面我不是很理解，第一次看到這樣的枕頭～盒子上寫會有涼涼的效果～有人有用過這樣的枕頭嗎？哈哈祝大家天天好心情🥰

Should Women in Film aim to foreground; seek to highlight themes, characters, or issues by bringing them into stark close-up? Or perhaps, instead, work in the background, shaking up the scenery?

With the timely arrival of the Singapore Rediscovers scheme, you can now enjoy discounted visits to Singapore’s most popular sights. Forged by a government keen on reviving the tourist economy, this initiative gives you and your kids a prized opportunity to jump back into the city’s colourful mix of culture, history and recreational hubs. 

Tourism credits worth up to $320 million are up for grabs, so there is little time to waste! 

The vouchers can be collected and used in registered tourist attractions across the city, including Madame Tussauds, HeadRock, SEA Aquarium, Singapore Zoo and many more. Your kids will be spoilt for choice, and may even rediscover the true charms of growing up in Singapore. 🇸🇬

Check out our latest post "Singapore Rediscovers: 15 Best Deals For You And Your Kids in 2020" to see some destinations where you can take the kids for a little adventure this coming school holidays. 👉 Link in our Bio

Which attraction will you start with? Leave your comments below.

Today is the first day of the ninth lunar month and it marks the start of the Nine Emperor Gods Festival （九皇爷诞）, it is one of the major Taoist celebrations and it was said that the scale of the festival was comparable to the Chinese New Year celebrations in Singapore during the olden days. 

There are a few major temples in Singapore dedicated to the worship of the Nine Emperor Gods, such as the Hougang Tao Mu Temple which I had attended the rituals last evening, I have been there yearly for many years but I did not necessary observe the practice of eating vegetarian meals throughout the 9 day celebrations. 😅

Due to the ongoing pandemic and safety distancing measures, the celebration was scaled down this year but devotees still came pouring in after midnight, of course with all the precautionary measures in place. 

Looking forward to the ninth day of the festival where it will reach the climax, there will be a procession which usually draws scores of devotees during normal period to send the deities back home at the seaside. 😀🙏 📍Singapore.🇸🇬

post_caption: Singapore 🥰fascinates me (and I am sure a lot of other people) by how the change in human and heritage landscape has been very significant. Behind this modern facade today there are layers and layers of memories, each telling a different aspect of the areas history. Many beautifully preserved examples of shophouses on hand today (constructed between the 1840s and the 1960s) across the island remain a visible canvas that portrays Singapore’s intriguing multicultural and architectural influences throughout the years. In 1970s and 1980s Singapore, pre-war shophouses were demolished to make way for urban development. Unfortunately, many of the tiles found in these buildings were sadly thrown out, but thanks to some passionate individuals, a number of them were saved, restored and preserved. With its intricacy and artistic detail, it is not hard to see why these tiles became a requisite of the Peranakan decorative repertoire (check out the stories🙃👆🏻if you want to know more about it) #singapore🇸🇬 #architecture #rediscoversingapore #painting #workshop @capellasingapore #сингапур  #art  #coffee #interiordesign #теловдело  @sassymamasg #sassymamasg #longboard #expatlivingsg @expatlivingsg #tattoo #graffiti #timeoutsg #meditation  #hipster @channelnewsasia #visitsingapore @visit_singapore #singaporeinsiders  #photography #jewelrydesigner  @chanelofficial  #chanel  @instagram #travelphotography  #kidsactivities

Magazine Road connects Havelock Road and Merchant Road. The road probably got its name due to its association with the old ammunition storage ground at Havelock Road. The road used to run along the Singapore River before reclamation and road works took place sometime in the 1980s. 

I cycled here one morning to check out the Tan Si Chong Su, the ancestral hall of the Tan Clan dating back to 1876. I was also surprised to find this brick structure that reminded me of Ximending's Red House in Taipei. 

From here one could also see the the Chin Swee flats constructed in the 1970s. In the background are also several mdoern architectural landmarks such as the 1974 Manhattan House by S.E.K Architects and most notably, the Landmark Tower, completed in 1985, designed by the late Timothy Seow, the architect behind the NTU School of  Arts, Design at Nanyang Technological University.

Also located in the vicinity is the famous Red Star Restaurant, founded in 1974 and known for their old school dim sum with trolley service. Further down from Magazine Road, and turning into Keng Cheow Street, you will find Masjid Omar Kampong Melaka, Singapore's oldest mosque dating back to 1820.

Fort Canning Hill area was once the centre of ancient Singapura that thrived in the 14th century, and was occupied by a palace with various buildings of political, religious and commercial significance.

 A spring used to exist on the west side of the hill, called pancur larangan or "forbidden spring", where the women of the ruler's household were said to bathe in ancient times. Many locals still call it the ‘Forbidden Hill and believe it is haunted as many have reported loud noises and thumps in park at night, as well as sightings of white hooded figures.

The hill, however, continued to be used by Imperial British forces and a massive underground bunker was built to serve as headquarters of the local military district.

Although the area is not very large, about 18 acres, there is so much to see. Unfortunately, there are no remains of the medieval palace that once dominated the hill. #fortcanning #fortcanningpark #singapore #sgig #iluvsg #rediscoversingapore #sosingaporelah #spiralstaircase

Toa Payoh has some really old flats too but the estate is being rejuvenated with these new apartments and facilities, thus it has some old and new vibes around the neighbourhood.

Some of us has the perspective that cooking takes a huge amount of effort, when meals an be prepared simply.

On my very first night, a German couple was preparing their dinner and I was surprised that they managed to prepare a bowl of vermicelli with vegetables and topped with sauce. 
Though I found out there's a mini rice cooker and an induction cooker with the pantry cupboards towards the end of my stay, they managed to use the electric water kettle to prepare their dinner. 
Isn't that inspiring for us create simple meals?

【新加坡第一家土耳其咖啡甜點屋 ｜甘榜格南】

第一次喝到土耳其咖啡是在 #甘榜格南[地點]#的ottoman turkish delight （59 bussorah street）喝到的，當下第一口就顛覆了我對咖啡的印象。

💁‍♀️原來土耳其咖啡又稱阿拉伯咖啡，是歐洲咖啡的始祖，從13世紀誕生已有八九百年歷史。煮法大致上沒有很大的改變，是連渣一起喝的。店家把咖啡粉放進叫Cevze的銅小壺，在加熱的沙子上慢慢煮。不加奶或煉奶，一般是直接加各種不同風味的糖。有趣的是喝剩下的渣拿來占卜，把杯子倒放至盤子上觀看杯子中的咖啡渣形狀算命哈哈！其表示意思如下**。

💁‍♀️除了咖啡也少不了甜點，尤其是果仁蜜餅（Baklava），或是直接音譯成巴拉瓦餅，是一種口味濃郁、甜膩的土耳其酥皮點心。 果仁蜜餅以層層酥皮製成，店家說有48層～每天新鮮出爐哈哈

💁‍♀️甜點也有土耳其冰淇淋。對面sultan餐廳也是他們家的，所以想要吃任何的美食在這兒都能吃得到！祝大家天天好心情！下集我們去「海底世界」哈哈🥰
	
**根據流傳如果杯子中有圖案，其表示意思如下：
* 圓形－ 婚姻、新戀情
* 方形－ 愉悅的婚姻或是家庭

Almost 8 years ago i told myself that i would only want a child when i am ready.. ⁣
⁣
Oh well to be honest no matter how prepared you are, you’ll be left unprepared still, there are so many new things to learn and so many things to deal with physically and mentally.. ⁣
I could totally get it when someone said they do not want a child, it’s personal choice.. ⁣
⁣
But don’t get me wrong.. At one point i really want a child.. and till now never ever regretting to have one on my own.. ⁣
Even though, life is getting more tough and harder now.. I feel life more fulfilling and purposeful.. Motherhood is the greatest thing and the hardest thing.. At the end of the day, i am going to raise a human being..⁣
⁣
To all struggling mommies, let’s think in this postive way: if today was rough and i feel that i am not good enough, i’ll try again tomorrow.. 💪🏻

Happy Birthday, Singapore 🇸🇬 .

•🍫 follow 📸 @gulajavatravelx 

We often hear about creating negative space and wonder what it is ? 
•
Simply put its creating black spaces in your photos and therein drawing the viewer’s eyes to the subject you are focusing on .
•
like in this photo, i have created dark spaces and used the light to focus on the mural of Willy Wonker.
•
whose your favourite Willy Wonker ? Gene Wilder or Johnny Depp ?

Missy. Our super senior cat is likely 13-15 years old. She is ultra picky about her food (older cats tends to lose taste and interest in food). It takes about 30-45mins to feed her daily. She nose still works perfectly though and will wake up to any smell of bonito flakes. 

She takes blood test on a yearly basis. And her health is still super good.

Today there are five different lines in the “subway”/“tube” system. The first line was the red line (north south) and it was launched in 1987. Following that was the green line from east to west in 1990. I remember taking it often when I was a kid when we visited my grandparents.
.
Part of the lines are built overground (swipe left) while the stations located in the central are mostly located underground.
.
The newest is the blue line (Down town line) that was built in 2013.
.

post_caption:
Fukushima Junmai Ginjo - un soire au chez @toku_izakaya_bar
.
Fukushima has a long history as a reputable sake region, with many of the prefecture’s 60 breweries dating back over 300 years. But it was the aftermath of the Tohoku Earthquake of 2011 that really propelled local brewers to strive for sake excellence; they united together to not only rebuild the local sake industry after the disaster, but to improve it. Uniquely, the producers share their knowledge on brewing methods, which are usually heavily guarded trade secrets. The variety of climates in Fukushima result in quite different brews: the mountainous inland area of Aizu-Wakamatsu is known for a richer, sweeter, more umami-laden type of sake to match the more hearty cuisine, while the coastal region of Hamadori brews light and refreshing varieties to match the local seafood.
. 
Ginjo (吟醸) is premium sake that uses rice that has been polished to at least 60 percent. It is brewed using special yeast and fermentation techniques. The result is often a light, fruity, and complex flavor that is usually quite fragrant.
.
The pairing between Junmai Ginjo and  a bitter Japanese Ginko with bonito flake create a sensational sweet flavour in the mouth. Unexpected recommendation from chef Masamitsu Kodamatsu. 👍🏽
.

When I tell people I stay in Sembawang, the word ‘ulu’ comes to everyone’s mind immediately. I’ve been living here for almost a decade but I’ve never really checked out the surrounding attractions until recently when I started to re-explore this place. 𖠿𖤣   
   
In fact, Sembawang has a lot outdoor activities to offer for families! I especially love spending time in nature at the sandy beach. Look at my daughter Brielle and you will see how relax and calm she is when she’s at the beach. I love the gentle sea breeze, seeing my child’s sandy toes, hearing the sound of waves and gazing at the little creatures on the beach.    
     
Besides Sembawang, there are also many other attractions for families to enjoy as you take your #Singapoliday. I recently realised there are plenty of fun-filled activities for families to enjoy right here in the city. For example, one of them is the Kelong Tour. Since my son Brayden enjoys crab hunting a lot, I guess going on a fishing tour would interest him too!    
     
In case you didn’t know, SingapoRediscovers has a plethora of deals and promotions across attractions, dining, tours and more – currently ongoing: https://www.visitsingapore.com/singaporediscovers/singaporediscovers-promotions  
 
I can’t wait to rediscover the best of our local culture, nature, art, heritage and more! Remember to stay safe and adhere to safe distancing measures when you're out!

Tug in a quite residential neighbourhood in Hougang holds an important legacy of the Japanese in Singapore.
The sprawling 30,000-square-metre Japanese Cemetery Park contains nearly 1,000 graves of Japanese civilians in Singapore and soldiers mostly from the early 20th century. This is the largest Japanese cemetery in Southeast Asia.
Founded by three Japanese brothel-keepers, the cemetery was built in 1891 as a burial ground for karayuki-san, or Japanese women brought here for prostitution, many of whom died poor and destitute.
Over the years, other Japanese civilians were buried here, mostly during the pre-war years. The cemetery was a burial ground until 1947, and became a memorial park in 1987. The Japanese Association of Singapore oversees its upkeep.
The well-kept park also holds the ashes of Japanese soldiers, marines and airmen killed during World War II, as well as the remains of Japanese war criminals who were executed at Changi Prison.

Koon Seng Road electric shophouses have been gazetted for conservation due to its 𝗵𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗿𝘆 & 𝗵𝗲𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗮𝗴𝗲 𝘃𝗮𝗹𝘂𝗲. With a hybridised blend of cultural injections, these shophouses still managed to showcase a uniformity in its 𝗮𝗿𝗰𝗵𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗰𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗲 & 𝗱𝗲𝘀𝗶𝗴𝗻, making it an #instaworthy spot for many locals & tourists.⁠
⁠
The external walls of these shophouses are decorated with Chinese couplets of good fortune, adorning entrances which are similar to the traditional residences in China. Shophouses were designed with 𝗳𝗹𝗼𝗿𝗮𝗹 & 𝗴𝗲𝗼𝗺𝗲𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗮𝗹 𝗰𝗲𝗿𝗮𝗺𝗶𝗰 𝘁𝗶𝗹𝗲𝘀 that were imported from Europe.⁠
⁠
⁠Furthermore, the various 𝗺𝗼𝘁𝗶𝗳𝘀 𝗼𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗳𝗮𝗰𝗮𝗱𝗲𝘀 are derived from mythical figures, which are usually symbols of good fortune & longevity, and reflected the wealth & status of the owner.⁠
⁠
Many elements of the 𝗞𝗼𝗼𝗻 𝗦𝗲𝗻𝗴 𝗣𝗿𝗲-𝗪𝗮𝗿 𝗦𝗵𝗼𝗽𝗵𝗼𝘂𝘀𝗲𝘀 are reflected in the designs of our hotel. ⁠
What other designs in our hotel have surprised you?⁠

Isn’t it planning for staycation make us very excited for now?!⁣
Last time planning overseas trip that made us very excited but for now i guess staycation is the only “holiday” we can do.. ⁣

Hoping for a birthday staycation in December, which is only few months away, how time flies! Seriously i can’t wait for 2020 to be over 😅 and see what will happen in 2021.. ⁣
⁣
Anyway took this photo at Capella Hotel in Sentosa Island, one of my fav hotels in Singapore.. ⁣
⁣
Capella Singapore was built in the 1880s to accommodate the British officers of the Royal Artillery and their families. Capella Singapore is made up of both modern and colonial buildings. Among them are Tanah Merah I and Tanah Merah II, bungalows built in the 1880s to accommodate the British Officers of the Royal Artillery, Coastal Defence Command based on Sentosa Island. Known as the Officers' Mess, it was where the officers and their families ate and relaxed by dancing and playing tennis. ⁣
They were given conservation status on Aug 7, 2000.⁣
The hotel receives its guests at both bungalows, which have been restored. ⁣
⁣

Fort Canning Park, an iconic hilltop landmark has witnessed many of Singapore’s historical milestones. The hill once sited the palaces of 14th century Kings and served as the Headquarters of the Far East Command Centre and British Army Barracks. The decision to surrender Singapore to the Japanese on 15 February 1942 was also made on the hill, in the Underground Far East Command Centre, commonly known as Battle Box.

Today, Fort Canning Park features nine historical gardens - the Pancur Larangan, Artisan’s Garden, Sang Nila Utama Garden, Jubilee Park, Raffles Garden, First Botanic Garden, Farquhar Garden, Spice Garden and Armenian Street Park.
The total length of the trail is about 2.5km. 
The park was originally known as Bukit Larangan, or 'Forbidden Hill' in Malay. 
Fort Canning —a verdant space surrounded by 18th century gateways and gazebos, was our first stop in our journey to

.
Take a day trip to this beautiful island and discover all the beauty that it has to offer. Visitors will be picked up from their homes 🏠 to the jetty and take a 15-min bumboat ride 🛶 to the island with our licensed tourist guide.
.
You will have a glimpse into Singapore's yesteryears, alongside 🌴 coconut rubber plantations, fish farms and Singapore’s last-remaining kampong (traditional village).
.
Originally known as Pulau Batu Jubin (Granite Stone Island in Malay), this 1020-hectare island’s granite quarries once provided the stone used to construct structures like the Istana and the Singapore-Johore Causeway.

resumed my weekend walk earlier this morning. Quite a satisfying one with 20,000
steps , and clocking about 9km. 
We started our expedition at a carpark , venturing to the “other side “ thru a heritage tree. We could have used a less threatening route to the hidden reservoir however the brather made us scaled up the muddy
, slippery and steep slope next to the Seah Im bunker.
.
Surprisingly, there was a grp who seemed to be in their mid 50s who managed to scale the steep slope so never say never! How can I lose to them right?! So yeah , I just had to do it! The rain last night made it even tougher! 

Anyway, I have visited the reservoir once few years ago through another trail. I like how elusive  and tranquil this place seemed to be. Do arm yourselves with insect repellent should u wish to venture there.
.
I edited the first pic , 2nd pic is the original color. Watch the clip on how i go all fours to scale the horrible slope 😐😫. Quite a fun experience nevertheless 🤔🤪 #rediscoversingapore #keppelhillreservoir

Happy Mid-Autumn Festival! 🏮🏮⁣
Time to eat mooncakes 🥮🥮🥮⁣
⁣
Every mooncake festival remind me of my late father, he always bought me mooncakes and celebrating this Chinese culture. The mooncakes he bought not as fancy as the mooncakes nowadays but it made my heart full! And when he no longer with us, my family didn’t really celebrate this festival anymore.. only when i moved to Singapore then i am immersed in this yearly celebration again.. The yummy mooncakes are very hard to resist, isn’t it?!⁣
⁣
Just want to show the beauty of art installation at Gardens by The Bay.. The Apricot Grove, which features apricot flowers at various stages of blooming, enhanced with gobo lighting effect to simulate falling flower petals, is inspired by the Chinese fable of Dong Feng “董奉”, who is a skilled and generous medical practitioner from the Three Kingdoms period ”三国时代”.⁣
⁣
This installation happening from 18 Sep 2020 - 4 Oct 2020, Lantern sets will be lighted up at the outdoor gardens from 7.00pm to 10.00pm and the Admission is free!⁣
⁣
It’s always crowded here and as usual do photoshop magic to make the picture “cleaner”. When i was there i was so tempted to remove my mask when taking photo, but i saw warning signs to keep mask on are everywhere and i wasn’t dare to take the risk, anyway it’s for my own safety and other people safety too!⁣

6 Oct  It’s OVER ~~ Wheeeee!!!🎢
.
We zipped, jumped and climbed to celebrate the end of PSLE!!!
.
Couldn’t just let the day go by without doing something memorable to celebrate the daughter’s effort and the resilience shown by the family in supporting Dana through her PSLE...The journey’s honestly been more stress-inducing than I thought and we couldn’t have made it without the love and encouragement we received. 
.
Really warmed my heart when I saw how Buddy ran to give his sister a tight hug this afternoon and innocently asked, “I got 满分💯for my 听写. Jiejie, how about you? Did you get full marks for PSLE too?” If only PSLE is that easy...🤦🏻‍♀️
.
Full marks or not, we know that as her parents, we have done our utmost to create a loving, safe and nurturing environment for our daughter and we entrust the next phase of her education to the Lord. 🙏🏻
.
Check out my IG story for highlights of our afternoon spent at @megaadventuresingapore. It’s our first time there but the kids loved it so much. Dana and David did the “Zip, Climb, Jump” combo while Buddy and I rode tandem on the MegaZip (It’s both our very first time ever on a zip line!!! 😅So cool to zip over the forest and beach! We loved it!). The kids then did some flips on the MegaBounce before the park closed. 
.
We arrived at 4pm and left by 6.30pm.  Ate dinner at @trapizza.sg next door before calling it a night (parking at Rasa Sentosa is free now). A very fun place for families! Tickets available via @klooksg and MegaAdventure’s website. We’ll definitely return👍🏼💯😁

#beautiful #temple of the #earth #god sitting with a moat. It was raining heavily, but it is a picture of #tranquility in the raging rain. It feels like overseas, and I wish I have more time to walk about and explore rather than the 15 mins or so I visit the island every 10 years or so. 

The middle aged couple living there tending to the temple must be feeling quite isolated from life on the mainland. The uncle I spoke to says it needs getting used to. But then I was also thinking, you get a peaceful life and an island to yourselves, isnt that great? Maybe in freedom, there is also a responsibility (manning the temple), and maybe isolation and peaceful life isn't such a great thing?

post_caption:
Postcards from #singapore 

Do you not find that this resembles a little like Europe? Memories of Amsterdam (yes I know, architecture and weather is very different) somehow flooded back.  Perhaps I miss travelling, perhaps the weather of evening breeze and cloudy skies was lovely, but I certainly love the  colorful buildings out there and the reflection on the #singaporeriver , and I feel transported out of SG momentarily yet feel appreciative that this is my beautiful country

Gai gai (街街) refers to going for a leisurely walk.. ⁣⁣
It’s a word we tell @dearbbkai everytime we bring him out.. As the things started to opening up slowly and almost back to normal, we took a courage to bring baby out weekly, capturing more moments because he grows up rapidly! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Happy to be able to witness his milestones as i still working from home for half of the week.. As you can see from IG stories now @dearbbkai able to rolls over, need to be extra cautious now.. ⁣⁣
Some of you asked me how me and hubby manage to take care newborn while working full time without any help.. We didn’t hire helper and our Moms are staying overseas, so we have no choice to take care baby on our own.. It’s not that hard to be honest, we both need to be very hands-on and have to get use do thing efficiently.. So if you are on the same situation like me, especially due to this pandemic you can’t get any help, don’t worry too much!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
📍Chijmes⁣⁣
CHIJMES (pronounced "chimes", acronym definition: Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus and ‘MES’ was added intentionally to make it sounds like chimes) is a historic building complex in Singapore.⁣
⁣⁣
The complex was used as a Catholic convent since 1852, with an acquired Caldwell House which was constructed in 1840–1841, an acquired Convent Orphanage house in 1855, the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus Chapel in 1904 and an acquired hotel complex for the girls' school in 1933. The Caldwell House, currently a wedding venue, and the Gothic-style chapel, renamed as CHIJMES Hall, currently a function hall and also a wedding venue, have both been gazetted as national monuments. The complex has been restored in 1996 for commercial purposes as a dining, shopping and entertainment centre with ethnic restaurants, shops and a function hall, providing a backdrop for musicals, recitals, theatrical performances and weddings. (Source: Wikipedia)⁣⁣
⁣⁣

⁣

⁣
I was stopped having caffeine when i got pregnant last year and now i am back enjoying coffee again.. My fav now is Latte.. What is your favourite coffee? ⁣

It is believed that the name “Yio Chu Kang” was derived from the early Chinese settlers’ practice of naming a riverside village after the family or clan that settled there or controlled it. Translated, Yio Chu Kang means a Yio (or Yeo) clan/family owns the house (chu) situated along the river (kang).

The history of bubble tea in Singapore began when the drink was first introduced to the country in 1992. It has undergone a few waves of popularity here. In the old days, bubble tea was served in a cocktail glass in “bubble tea huts”. But long queues at bubble tea shops, now serving only takeaway bubble tea, is a common sight today. How has this craze managed to sustain itself for this long and continue to find favour among Singaporeans? So long story short, while many regard it as a fad, others deem it to be a classic example of how a simple drink can continue to appeal to different taste preferences and be enjoyed by people across generations... in 5 years I decided to try it 😂finally! Ps. Telok Kurau Road
connects Changi Road to Marine Parade Road and was named after a fishing village named Telok Kurau on East Coast Road. According to Infopedia, the name, Telok Kurau, means "mango fish bay" in Malay. Mango Fish (Polynemus risua) is in the threadfin family. More commonly however, Ikan Kurau is also used to refer to "threadfin", also known as "ngoh her" in Hokkien.

I cycled here recently after reading up on Siglap. The site in this illustration is the junction of Joo Chiat Place and Telok Kurau Road. The unit where Fu Fa Coffeeshop is right now was previously occupied by Long Fu Coffeeshop (隆福). One of its stalls was Nam Huat Chicken Rice (南發雞飯) which started business in the 1970s and closed in 2014.

Next to the coffeeshop was Chang Cheow Ser, a 24-year old provision shop which started in the former Siglap Market. The provision shop was named after it's founder and it had a distinct iron grill facade. The unit has been taken over by Sunric Stores (a convenience store).

The row of single-storey structures here are located opposite the former Telok Kurau West Primary School which first opened in 1962. It joined two other schools, the Telok Kurau Malay Girls' School and Telok Kurau East School to form Telok Kurau Primary School in 1985. The current school's earliest history goes back to 1926 as the Telok Kurau English School. The late Mr Lee Kuan Yew studied there in 1931.

Drawn with @adobe Photoshop and @wacom_singapore Intuos Pro.

Super trees 🍃🌱🌿💚🙌🏽✨
.
Each Supertree is made up of four major components: the reinforcement concrete core, the trunk, planting panels, and a canopy. Designed to resemble trees, they’re meant to function like them as well. 
Some are equipped with solar panels to store energy for the nightly light show, while others are used as air exhaust receptacles to help cool the Flower Dome and Cloud Forest conservatories. On top of that, they all collect rainwater for use in irrigation and fountain displays. Photosynthesis, cooling the air, and storing rainwater, like actual trees indeed!

If the leopard and tiger look familiar and remind you of @hawparvilla.sg in @singapore, you are right. 

This temple building was constructed in 1930 with a donation from Aw Boon Haw and Aw Boon Par, brothers best known for developing the Tiger Balm ointment. They are, of course, the brothers who also built Haw Par Villa. 

🪔The temple is 15 metres tall and houses a 300-ton statue of Buddha. 

🪔The statue is surrounded by a seemingly endless chain of lights, leading to the temple’s popular name, “Temple of a Thousand Lights”. 

🪔 it houses an ebony and mother-of-pearl replica of Buddha’s footprint and a piece of bark from the original Bodhi tree under which Buddha sat. This replica of the footprint was found on top of Adam’s Peak in Sri Lanka, a mountain named after the belief that its summit housed the first man Adam’s crypt. 

🪔The temple’s architecture reflects an eclectic mix of Chinese, Thai and Indian cultural influences.

#loronghalusbridge  is a classic bridge that displays a contemporary design. bridge is only limited to pedestrians. The bridge stands over the Serangoon river. Older Singaporeans will immediately associate Lorong Halus with garbage, as it was Singapore’s refuse dumping ground from the 1970s till the 1990s.

Commuting by public transport again recently.. Appreciating those ME time moments on my way back and forth daily..⁣
⁣
Do you realize art galore happening at almost every MRT station in Singapore?⁣
⁣
And this is one of them.. ⁣
At Newton station, the artist created a monochrome drawing of the area in year 2200. The 11m by 9m picture forms the backdrop to the station's escalators and commuters can marvel at the artist imagined city, comprising layers of stacked buildings with snaking highways.⁣
⁣
Don’t you love that crossing escalator with art at the background? To be honest it was very easy to take this photo with zero human traffic at escalator, just need to wait for the off-peak timing in between train arrival.⁣
⁣
Which one is your favourite MRT station in Singapore?

📍 Newton MRT (Downtown Line) ⁣

Tucked away in the Tampines heartland is Tampines Eco Green, a 36.5-hectare ecological park that resembles a savannah with marshlands, secondary forests and freshwater ponds. It has no lights or pavements. the wildlife at Tampines Eco Green is still quite rich. opened in 2011, the Tampines Eco Green Park is a nature-lover’s delight. In the middle of high-density HDB flats, this 36.5 hectare park, situated in the east of our island nation, is home to a wealth of biodiversity.

Warehouse
.
.
.

The Warehouse Hotel was built in 1895 along the Singapore River as part of the Straits of Malacca trade route. At that time, the area was a hotbed of secret societies, underground activity, and liquor distilleries. Today, while much of that history has disappeared, The Warehouse Hotel has been meticulously restored as a modern 37-room boutique hotel, focusing on heritage and local culture.

The saddest thing about the day trip was: I wanted to see Lazarus the most, but we just ended up walking in heavy thunderstorm,  never made it to the beach, and all we did was spent time under a shelter to wait out the heavy rain with a sad kitty hiding from the cold in the grass patch,  and a earthworm (I think) for company.  I left our lunch bag somewhere, dont know where, and we didn't have lunch. Lols. Makes the trip all that more memorable, isnt it? We had to make our way back to St John for the boat, and we managed to find our lunch bag sitting in the rain. Lols. I left it on the floor when taking a picture, and  ran off without it and it sat in the thunderstorm for over an hour. Nice. Monkeys were climbing over the roofs of the gazebos, and we had to head for the pier to have our  lunch and some shelter. What a day!

The majestic and imposing City Hall has been the focal point of many of the most important events in the history of Singapore.
-	Admiral Lord Louis Mountbatten, on behalf of the Allied forces, accepted the surrender of the Japanese forces on 12 September 1945 in City Hall to end World War II in Singapore
.
-	On 5 June 1959, Mr Lee Kuan Yew declared self-governance and together with his eight cabinet ministers took their Oaths of Allegiance and Oaths of Office in the City Hall Chamber
.
-	The Malaysia Proclamation was read out here in 1963 when Singapore was no longer under British rule. The first Malaysia Day was also held at the Padang which was outside the City Hall
.
-	When Singapore was no longer part of Malaysia, the first National Day Parade was also held at the Padang in 1966. The steps of the City Hall have since been used as a VIP seating area when National Day Parades were held there, the latest being the 2020 NDP held recently
.
-	The City Hall was also the place where Singapore’s second Prime Minister, Mr Goh Chok Tong had his inauguration ceremony and the swearing-in of his cabinet in 1990
.
-	In 2015, The City Hall, together with the adjacent Old Supreme Court Building, has been converted into the National Gallery Singapore
.
As an officially gazetted National Monument of Singapore since 14 February 1992, do take some time to visit this historic building together with the Old Supreme Court Building (which was also gazetted as a National Monument)
.
.
.

We have memories longer than the road that stretches out ahead because most things will end but memories last forever.
.
I have seen so many photos of everyone coming here to catch a glimpse of the first Apple floating Store, guess I am one of the last few people who comes here after all the hype is over. This place used to be bustling with evening joggers and visitors from both local and abroad. Nowadays its just peaceful and calm. Even the water taxis are no longer in operation. I believe that most places would be the same but its somehow another unique experience. It feels great to be out again!
.
Photo taken with Kase plug in filter in the Nikon Z 7. I rate this filter 7/10 for quality, no color cast, affordable and highly versatile. The 3 points deducted were for the scary experience mounting it on and off and cannot be easily changed on the go.
.

Alliance Française de Singapour @afsingapour was founded in 1949 for people who want to enjoy a truly unique and authentic French experience. Each year, hundreds of cultural events are organized for around 15,000 to 20,000 persons: exhibitions, films, Q&A sessions with directors, actors or producers, workshops with French artisans, concerts, story-telling or meet-the-author at la médiathèque, etc. Because Only developing mutual understanding and going beyond cross-cultural boundaries through the discovery of languages and cultures can help humanity to live in a more respectful world. The three of us have decided that when we meet, we do something that’s out of our comfort zone. We chose to go on a walk this time and someone’s prawn mee craving sealed our route/end point. We flagged off @gardensbythebay, walked high and low round the bay, through the Sports Hub, Tanjung Rhu, Kampong Arang, down Katong where we made a pit stop @bopgelato, and finally crossed the checkered flag at Beach Road Prawn Mee. 
During our 11+ km walk, we spoke about anything and everything - where we would go if we could travel (have you had difficult travelling companions and how did you cope?); Covid conspiracy theories; NS memories (not mine); Emily in Paris (so bad yet addictive); Birkin bags; and what our next ‘adventure’ should be. I think the conversations kept our feet moving.
.
If you’ve got any suggestions for our next activity, do share!
.
.

Kampong – a term to describe traditional villages or urban slum areas in towns and cities. 

In the early days, there used to be many kampongs scattered all over Singapore. However, with development and urbanization, these kampongs have been replaced with modern skyscrapers.

As an urban kid, kampong lifestyle is something that I find it hard to visualize and the only references I have of it are from my grandparents’ narration of their happy childhood days back in the kampong era.

Upon knowing that there is still the last kampong in Singapore (Kampong Lorong Buangkok), I jumped at the chance to explore it. It was a strange feeling walking through the kampong. Despite being surrounded by the all-so-familiar modern architectures and bustling roads, time seemed to come to a standstill here. Low-rise single-storey houses made of wood with zinc roofs instead of high-rise apartments; lush greeneries instead of dense man-made structures; a peaceful and quiet surrounding instead of the hustle and bustle of the city, this is indeed a whole new world to me!

I took my time to explore and admire the place, soaking up the atmosphere of this lovely location (and at the same time trying very hard to ignore the constant attacks from the bloodsucking mosquito..). This visit has definitely changed my impression of Singapore – there is more to Singapore than meets the eye!!

A very impromptu decision to visit The S.E.A Aquarium this morning and a decision which paid off!
Both boys were excited from the moment they reached the entrance and ran amok inside! It was surprising there was a fair amount of visitiors even at 10am in the morning and the Safety Distance Ambassadors had their hands full coordinating the crowd! Aldon was so excitied throughout the day after visiting that he drew his impression of a ship wreck in the blue ocean and various sea animals during his arts class in the late evening! All in all, a great Sunday bonding with the boys!
Fyi - They are running a special promotion for Singaporeans and PRs at the SEA Aquarium til 31st August! Discounted ticket prices + Free Liho bubble tea per ticket purchased!

Yay we finally went to the Artscience Museum! In the Future World:
Where Art Meets Science exhibition, there were lots of fun for us as we explored the interactive installations. Some of them were breathtaking and lots were simply very cute!!!! 

We highly recommend a visit there because it's just too fun! There's proper crowd control and you will be given a pair of gloves since there are lots of interactive screens. Sanitisers are available everywhere for the younger ones who can't keep their gloves on. 

Highlighting a few artworks

Please don't feed the monkeys 🐵 
You will do them more harm than good ! With  human development encroaching further and further into their habitat, we have become close neighbours ... Macaques have come to learn that humans provide easy access to food and continue to rely on them. Sadly, a lack of education on appropriate human behaviours around wildlife has led to a rise in human-macaque interaction and conflict. For example, people feed monkeys to have a closer look at these fascinating creatures. Some people even think the monkeys are starving. 
In 2019 the Jane Goodall Institute Singapore (JGIS) in partnership with the Longtailed Macaque Working Group launched the campaign to solve this problem: a three-year "No Feeding" campaign aims to teach park-goers and residents near macaque hotspots not to feed the monkeys. Did you hear anything about “Monkey Guards”? A team of residents in hotspots who have been trained in macaque behaviour and appropriate ways of dealing with them. The aim isn’t to eliminate the sightings of macaques, but to create a safe and respectful barrier between people and macaques. #rediscoversingapore

Regardless of whether you are a first time visitor or not, this place will never fail to surprise you. It might be a bit of a travel for those who don’t live in the West, but  every single time I come here to take a break from the city bustle it makes me feel better. When was the last time you spent a quiet moment just doing nothing – just walking around or watching the wind blowing the tree limbs, or waves rippling on a pond... 🙃?
Over the years, this garden has undergone several changes with new features added to it, integrating brightly colored buildings with the natural environment: the structural arrangement of the pavilions and towers are balanced in terms of their height and size in the tradition of ensuring that everything blends harmoniously with each other and merge into a beautiful combination. BtW it’s a perfect time, because this place especially popular during the  Mid-Autumn Festival celebrations. 
Ps. FYI The new Science Centre will be built on the north shore of this place.

I went to this rustic island off the north eastern part of Singapore, knowing that the weather wasn’t too favourable.

Thankfully it was bright and sunny for at least the first half of the day and it only rained extremely heavily for about 45 minutes, in which I thankfully managed to seek refuge at Ah Ma’s Drink Stall.

From climbing up to see beautiful quarries, to seeing random shrines and temples. From wild boar and big lizard scares to feeding thirsty dogs with half of my water. From beautiful butterflies to nasty spiders. My adventure to this tranquil island is made more tranquil with much lesser crowds and social distancing.

Yet, I feel full and energised. I feel rejuvenated and refreshed. And I feel glad to have learnt so much on this trip and to have feel so much in touch with the finer things in life.

Dear Pulau Ubin, or rather, Pulau Batu Jubin, thank you so much for the fun! So great to see you after 5 over years! My stamina may not be there, but my spirit is still going strong! Take care and till next time!

#PulauUbin #islandlife #underrated #jetty #sidetrip #finds #rediscoverSingapore #island #Singapore #sg #MajulahSingapura

Rediscovering Singapore 🇸🇬. Yesterday late afternoon walk at the Changi Coastal Trail. We had a sunny day, the sea breeze is cooling, making the walk really enjoyable. Swipe ⬅️to see the beautiful beach. Rediscovering the natural beauty of our little island. After the walk is feasting time. @littleislandbrew has a good range of craft beer and the food is fantastic. We love the freshly made pizza 🍕, soft and tender beef brisket. Delicious food, great company, wonderful weather: All the right combination 👌

The beauty of cities is that they offer us unexpected moments, serendipitous encounters. Today, that came in the form of running into @yipyewchong who is the artist of many of the street art of Chinatown. Using these murals as our laboratory, the life of the early Chinese immigrants comes alive with his artwork. In this case, the dazzling costumes, realistic backdrops, props and acrobatic fighting of Cantonese Opera which was all around early Chinatown.

Psst : the full length of this colourful mural will be posted on IG stories tomorrow (friyay!)

Lastly, big thanks YC for taking time to chat with our friends this morning! 
.
.

During the Second World War, a hill in the park was the site of one of the last and fiercest battles fought by the Malay Regiment against the invading Japanese army, the Battle of Bukit Chandu. 
Kent Ridge Park is part of the Pasir Panjang Historic District, which focuses on World War II battlefield events in western Singapore. 
Near to the top of the ridge, there is a commemorative heritage site marker which shows the area where the Battle of Pasir Panjang of 1942 was fought.

Art doesn’t have to be found on the walls of a gallery. While Singapore certainly has its share of world-class museums, exhibitions and art spaces, it’s also home to a wealth of street art and iconic wall murals.

Go on a hunt through Singapore’s diverse neighbourhoods—from the South Asian enclave of Little India to the lively streets of Chinatown—and discover art that will both inspire and expand your artistic sensibilities.

The Singapore Food Festival (SFF) is going virtual for 2020, and there’s plenty on the menu for those interested in the country’s vibrant gastro scene. The online event takes place across the last two weekends in August and will offer virtual food tours, live masterclasses (count us in on the éclair-making class) and chef collaborations. More tasty details over on the site…
